Traveling with children reminds me that adults have a tendency to over complicate things and take things for granted. Travel is different in all the best ways, at least in my opinion… when you take along little ones and see it through their eyes. 

Children travel with open minds and hearts. Ready to try new things with little to no hesitation. Meet new people without clouded world views. Appreciate the little things most adults would miss. Soaking up everything like little sponges. 

I genuinely think traveling with my kids forces me to slow down and take things in. Experiencing in a way I may not have otherwise. Learning from them alongside them! 

It may be less work to go without them, but then I think about all I’d miss. 🫶🏼

⚠️ Did you know drowning is the number one cause of accidental death for infants and young children between the ages of 1-4? 

Water safety is a big priority for us, especially with our travels constantly taking us to places surrounded by different waterways. We have never been in a place long enough to do lessons and it’s always bothered me. So I jumped at the opportunity in our transition while visiting with family to do so. 

ISR lessons are a big commitment but worth every minute. Children from 6 months to 6 years of age learn how to use Infant Swimming Resource’s Self-Rescue skills to save themselves.

Infant Swimming Resource’s Self-Rescue survival swimming program is a 4-6 week course, scheduled 5 days per week, Monday through Friday, for 10 minutes each day.

Even though both have completed the program, the work is not done. Supervision and practice, is vital!

I highly recommend finding ISR lessons near you. Even if you think your little one can swim, I think it’s still important. Because falling into water and panicking is a whole different scenario than getting in on their own. Help them learn the skills that could potentially save themselves one day. 

@watch.me.swim  shares a ton of info and can help you find an instructor near you.

PSA
I could give ZERO flying 🦆s about anyones feelings, politics, or personal convictions when it comes to keeping my children and I safe!

There is no such thing as manners or proper etiquette with creeps that can’t take a hint. Be firm. Let them know you’re not comfortable and they need to get all the way lost!. And then move on yourself quickly while staying aware of your surroundings. 

ALWAYS making sure you’re prepared if they don’t. #wheresthepewpewemoji!? 

You owe no strangers out there on the trails, camping, WHEREVER… that are giving you bad vibes kindness! PERIOD. 

Momma instinct is a powerful tool. Use it. 

Have fun, but stay safe 🫶🏼!

Before I can share where we’re going, I figure it’d be fun to show where we’ve been. 

The beginning. 
Tired of being apart 2-3 plus months at a time we made a big decision. To chase 🏗 with D.
Sold our home. All of our belongings that didn’t fit inside this travel trailer. 
Hitting the road at the beginning of what we didn’t know would be a major 💩 show aka c#v*d. We launched at the beginning of 2020.

The 🦠 actually was a strange blessing. Because of all the closures and rules we avoided most public places and fell in love with the outdoors. Something our family never had time for in the regular grind we were caught up in back home. 

Tiny living makes or breaks families and although there was definitely a transition period, we thrived in it. Our children were young enough to not really know any different, and to them having daddy and mommy regularly was what mattered most. 

Our little travel trailer was tiny but it was home. Because we were all there together. The views and the backyard constantly changed, but our home remained the same and that was enough. 

Our only complaints were the lack of outdoor storage for the things we added to our set up and no room in the master. So that lead us to our next home on wheels.

To be continued…

Will we still be RVing?
Moving?
Bought a house?

————————————
Full-time RV family

Travel trailer

It’s a family affair and love that our boy loves any chance he gets to use tools with his daddy. 

Here’s a little piece of a project we’re working on. 😉

Where we’ve been continued…
We knew we planned to continue road life, chasing cranes with D. So we quickly decided to look into fifth-wheels for more storage underneath, taller ceilings, and more room in the master. 

We fell in love with the Montana High Country 335BH layout and was excited to make it our own. It truly became home on wheels 2.0 for us and we grew a lot here. Literally, having baby O! 

Weathering snow apocalypses to smoking hot stints bordering Mexico that rig was so good to us! 

Selling it was not easy, but I began falling in love with travel that didn’t involve hauling this beast around. Realizing maybe just maybe we could downsize even further…

To be continued.

Continued continued… 
Two summers ago kids and I headed out on a month long road trip West. To states we haven’t been. With just the truck, a tent, and a few tiny unique accommodations sprinkled in between. 

This is where I fell in love with solo mom travel. Obviously we love us all being together, but Ds job had been changing so much it was looking like we may be apart again some. So I quickly figured out how to continue traveling just the kids and I. Starting in just a tent and our truck. 

Tent camping is a lot of work, but it feels so good accomplishing the work together. The littles love to help and quickly we became a team. 

There is nothing like pitching a tent in the PNW, being steps away from the moody coast and immersed in the Redwoods. Or camping in Colorado surrounded by Rockies on the horizon. You truly feel like you’re surrounded by nature. Sometimes a little too surrounded 🤣.

While tent camping will always be my favorite. It’s not practical for long trips in my opinion. Plus there’s all the work every time rain or shine. We have gotten caught up in crazy weather enough that I knew this wasn’t the ultimate solution for traveling more freely kids and I, but it will do on occasion. 

Leaving me to wonder what we could do next…

P.s thank you @cruaoutdoors for taking a chance on us and being apart of all of our camping shenanigans. Our Xtent will always come along our adventures no matter where they take us.

Continued x3

Solo mom tent camping escalated to a rooftop tent fast 😅🤣. With no regrets! We got to camp in some pretty epic places with this setup! Seaside on the Texas coast, way out west in the desert, and in the Appalachian mountains. 

Building this set up and piecing together everything was so much fun! I loved having everything right on the truck. Making it simple with the kiddos. From solar, to a fridge/freezer, and even a shower set up. 
We loved how much comfier it was to not sleep on the ground. &&& you can’t beat the views from up high! 

The cons to this set up long term are very similar to tent camping. You have to set it all up. Which doesn’t take much, but still a thing. If you want to go anywhere you have to pack it all back up. So it limits your mobility and getting around quickly. 

Safety is also a factor to consider. It’s harder to quickly leave if you need to. Especially with tent attached to truck. Tent camping you can just ditch your tent in an emergency. There are ways I prepared for those instances in case, but over all if I’m going to travel with the kids solo for longer I’d love something that’s not as hard to go when needed. 

Now hang in with me for one more installment of where I’ve been, to understand where I’m going! I thoroughly enjoy reading your comments along the way ♥️!

Continued pt. 4 LAST post 😉 

@moterra camping van rentals should come with a disclaimer… “Be warned your experience will leave you longing for MORE. Side effects include non stop day dreaming of more tiny, but BIG adventures! Spiraling you into wanting to purchase your own adventure rig saying bye bye to all your 💸💸💸. Until you can, you’ll be addicted to renting over and over again to fulfill the itch.”

I LOVED loved van travel. The two experiences with @moterra left me changed! Realizing we totally could downsize even further and rock some awesome extended road trips! Having all that we need with the outdoors being our playground (responsibly of course). 

Tent camping and the RTT are and were awesome, but to get to places we’d want to go it makes more sense to have a solid rig to make those longer trips. But the travel trailer and fifth-wheel were also just too big based on our experience to travel quickly and as remotely…the way I’d like. 

A con I knew I’d hit if van life was going to be for me was the price tag of the ones ready to go off the lot. All decked out in off grid goodies. Hard to justify when some start off more expensive than our first house.
I could build I suppose, but that takes time and help. And the way my life is set up with my hard working husband building the world one crane at a time… Not so sure that’s the move to make…

So that’s what lead me to…

Kids and I will be traveling on extended road trips all over the US! I wanted something solid, but also with a small footprint. We have big plans in the near future and price was also a big deciding factor. Just couldn’t pull the trigger on a van or even class c (shopped both and even almost pulled trigger on one) when we have goals to meet and part time roots to put down. Cheers to being responsible and finding balance 🙌🏼

Some assumed we may join D somewhere far away. And we still might, but while he’s in places that don’t make sense for us to join, we have the freedom to roam now without a huge rig.

Hey mommas,
Thought I’d reintroduce a little bit of my purpose for this account. It’s funny because 3 years ago I wouldn’t recognize myself or this content. I’d be shocked and a little impressed. But yes, secretly a little scared.

If you find yourself struggling to leave the house to go to the grocery store alone with your kids, I’ve been there.

If you’re struggling to attempt the zoo or a local attraction alone with your kids, I’ve been there.

If camping, hiking, and flying alone with your kids is out of your comfort zone, I’ve been there too. 

Taking baby steps and deep breaths is how I overcame my anxiety to leave the house. And yes that’s right, there was a time after I had my brand new babies I was nervous to even leave the house. 

I use to turn down plans with family or friends. Thinking about all the things that could go wrong with little ones and how we’d inconvenience others who had to witness it 🙄. 

&& let’s be honest moms having babies 2020 and on have had a whole new era of anxiety to overcome with the 🦠 crazy circus. I don’t even think I need to explain that. 

A big reason I am passionate about sharing, isn’t to brag or show off. It’s to encourage and hopefully empower you to make steps to being free of fear to leave your home with your kids. Helping you put practices in place so that you feel comfortable, prepared, and safe. Sharing gear recommendations that actually help and I stand by. Most importantly being your cheerleader clapping for every small step that leads to the big ones. 

As moms today in this world it’s easy to be overwhelmed with fear, but I’m here to remind you of 2Timothy 1:7. 

If you take anything away from my account remember this, I’m not super woman. I am just a mom who started where you are who was determined to not let fear stop her from living and exploring. If you know a momma who could use a little inspo or maybe she’s a mom to be, tag her in the comments. Thank you for being here and being my cheerleader, encouraging me to do the same for all of you. Means more than you know!

📍 Black Hills National Forest

📌Where Can You Camp in the National Forests?

Camping is allowed anywhere within the forest boundaries unless that particular forest has restricted certain places.

📌Some universal rules to follow
👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼
(( but always check with the specific NF you plan to visit prior for info on fire bans, weather, or specific rules to that forest. ))

🌲 Stay in designated or established campsites when available. There is no sense in trampling and destroying more vegetation.
🌲 Don’t create new trails, even short cuts through campgrounds. Stay on trails and roads.
🌲 Be conscious of fragile water banks. Excessive foot traffic can cause erosion problems and destroy creek and river banks.
🌲 Dispose of trash in receptacles if you are in a campground, otherwise pack out your trash.
🌲 Use existing fire rings and put your fire out cold.
🌲 If bathrooms are not available, dispose of human waste properly. Including grey water! 
🌲 Wildlife live in national forests. Proper food storage is extremely important. Never leave food out or in a tent – always secure it in your vehicle (bears will get in cars for food too!), in bear proof lockers if available at your campsite, a bear canister, or hang it in a bear bag. 
🌲 Have fun, but please don’t be the loud group that nobody wants to be camped near.

I remember reading someone’s comment they thought Indiana Sand Dunes was boring and not worth stopping. They’re wrong. 

We spent a total of 3 weeks in the area broken up over two visits. And I would absolutely come back again. 

We stayed at both Dunewood which is the National Park’s campground and at Indiana Sand Dunes State Park’s campground! 

Dunewood’s sites are huge! They have room for RV, tent, and more all on one site. They’re shaded which is a good thing because there are no hook ups here. When we were there the weather was perfect and in the 60s at night (this was July). 

There are trails, but there is no direct access to Lake Michigan here either. BUT you’re close enough to ride your bike or drive a short distance. So it’s still a great spot in close proximity to all the different “beaches”. 

We were very bummed to have to pivot our plans heading West to go to Indiana for warranty repairs. I wanted to make the most of it so I decided to spend a little time at Indiana Sand Dunes. We had no idea how much we’d love Lake Michigan! We wound up extending our time around it and exploring two more states we didn’t plan on. To enjoy it even more from different perspectives.

School House Beach 
📍 Washington Island, Wisconsin 

School House Beach is one of 5 beaches in the world like it. Covered entirely in limestone rocks with no grain of sand in sight, a visit to this beach is truly a one-of-a-kind experience. 

The water at Schoolhouse Beach State Park in Wisconsin is crystal clear, letting you see down to the bottom where the limestone rocks sit.

The rocks are smoothed by the water, but also from the glaciers that moved through the area and deposited them here millions of years ago.

The rocks are so unique, in fact, that a law was passed making it illegal to remove rocks from Schoolhouse Beach.

You can skip the stones, stack them, or photograph them; however, it's important to respect the law and refrain from vandalizing them or taking them home.

Its a beautiful beach and view of Lake Michigan. The water is so clear and clean.

Woodland Park Campground has both PHU and dispersed sites (no hookups). It is pretty popular and fills up during summer months. There’s sites you can book in advance online and then there’s FCFS. Have you visited a rainforest?

Washington state is full of wonder and adventure, but did you know that Washington is also home to four rainforests? That’s right! You can find four temperate rain forests on the Olympic Peninsula which is located on the West coast of Washington. It’s one of the best places in the entire world to see this type of ecosystem and it's one of the top things to do in the Pacific Northwest. 

🍃 Hoh Rainforest 
🍃 Quinault Rainforest 
🍃 Queets Rainforest
🍃 Bogachiel Rainforest

The most popular is the Hoh Rainforest. When visiting, make sure you set your GPS to the Hoh Rain Forest Visitor Center to get an accurate arrival time. The visitor center is about 30+ minutes after you turn off at the Hoh Rainforest sign.

Most popular trails in the Hoh 
✨ The Hall of Mosses Trail
✨ The Spruce Nature Trail 
✨ Hoh River Trail, There are multiple camping spots throughout this trail and the last stop on the trail is Glacier Meadow.

All four of Washington’s rainforests are located on the Olympic Peninsula that is also home to the Olympic National Park. The Olympic Peninsula is a massive peninsula located to the West of Seattle and you could easily spend a week on the peninsula enjoying all that it has to offer! Aside from the rainforests, you can find clear lakes, gorgeous beaches, and tons of trails with breathtaking views. 

We will definitely be back because we barely scratched the surface! Highly recommend going in off season to avoid crowds like we did. Mid October-Early November.
